==Old English==

===Etymology===
Germanic ''*deuza-'', from Indo-European ''*dheus-''.

Germanic cognates include Old High German [[tior]] (German [[Tier]]), Old Saxon [[dior]] (Dutch [[dier]]), Old Norse {{Latinx|''dȳr''}} (Swedish [[djur]]), Gothic [[𐌳𐌹𐌿𐍃]].  The IE root also led to Lithuanian ''dvēsti'', Lettish ''dvēsele'', Old Slavic ''duša'' (Russian [[душа]]).

